<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Waiting for DPRK, U.S. Regarding Inspections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0501080494 Paris AFP in English 0248 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0501080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Vienna, Jan 5 (AFP) -- The International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) said Tuesday [4 January] that up to now it 
had not been contacted either by North Korea [DPRK] or the 
United States regarding inspections of North Korean nuclear 
facilities. 
  A spokesman of the Vienna-based organisation said the IAEA 
was "waiting for one of the two sides to get in touch with us." 
  Contacts between North Korea and the IAEA have been 
suspended 
since Pyongyang, which is suspected of working to develop 
nuclear weapons, refused to let IAEA inspectors into all its 
nuclear facilities. 
  In December, the IAEA rejected a North Korean offer to allow 
partial inspection of its facilities. 
  The IAEA said it had insisted on being allowed to see all 
North Korea's nuclear facilities and was "ready to resume its 
inspections at any time." 
  Pyongyang said it was willing to let IAEA inspectors view 
five of its seven nuclear facilities. 
  But at the two others, a nuclear reactor and a uranium 
reprocessing plant, both at Yongbyon, North Korea said IAEA 
inspectors would only be allowed to put new film in the cameras 
already installed to monitor work at the facilities. 
  It was a request to visit these two sites, which Pyongyang 
says are military facilities with no nuclear role, which sparked 
North Korea's decision in February to suspend inspections of 
existing sites and threaten to withdraw from the Nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

