<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industry Representatives Respond </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0501101694 Berlin DIE WELT in German 5 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0501101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by "HH/wtm": "Fewer Investments in Russia?"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn -- In view of the latest threats by Russian 
right-wing extremist Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, representatives of 
German industry have warned against a decreasing willingness to 
invest in Russia. The winner of the Russian elections had 
threatened with World War III; he talked about stationing 
300,000 troops in Germany and about claims to German 
compensation payments for damage done in World War II. 
  The chairman of the East Committee of the German Economy, 
Otto Wolff von Amerongen, said: "The new Zhirinovskiy element 
will not increase people's willingness to invest." The 
Bonn-based Federation of German Chambers of Industry and 
Commerce said that "the climate is deteriorating," and this 
affects all sectors of industry. 
  The Federal Government reacted to Zhirinovskiy's threat 
quite 
calmly. Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt told DIE WELT that 
German-Russian trade relations have "a sound base founded on 
mutual interests." They have "proved solid" also in the 
difficult times of the Cold War. Rexrodt cannot see 
Zhirinovskiy's positions shaking these foundations: "Yeltsin and 
the Russian Government still consider a further expansion of 
trade relations with the West, and especially with Germany, 
their top priority," Rexrodt pointed out. Moscow is well aware 
that the industrialized nations and the international financial 
institutions must be of first importance in the reform process, 
Rexrodt said. 
  "The economy is not panicking," Karl-Hermann Fink, manager 
of 
the East Committee of the German Economy, said. He said that 
all the long-term projects are continuing. 
  Within the German gas industry, which buys some 30 percent 
of 
its supplies from Russia, there is no trace of alarm. Neither 
the market leader Ruhrgas in Essen, nor Wintershall Erdgas 
Handelshaus GmbH, the German partner of the Russian Gazprom, are 
planning any emergency measures. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

