<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Asylum Seekers Decrease by 100,000 in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0501092694 Hamburg BILD in German 5 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0501092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg BILD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Einar Koch: "100,000 Asylum Seekers Less"] </F>
  [Text] The new asylum laws are showing an effect! 
  The number of asylum seekers last year decreased by 
approximately 100,000 -- from 438,000 to 322,000, which is 26.4 
percent less than in 1992. This is what Federal Interior 
Minister Manfred Kanther (Christian Democratic Union) says in 
his latest asylum report (which is still secret). The upshot: 
"The declining tendency has stabilized." In the last month, in 
December, there were no more than 14,000 asylum applications (in 
the same month of the previous year, the figure was 32,000). 
  The main countries of origin in 1993 were what is left of 
Yugoslavia (73,000), Romania (73,000), Bulgaria (23,000), and 
Turkey (20,000). 

</TEXT>

