<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pangalos: Bosnia `Top Priority' of EU Presidency </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0401140994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0401140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Theodhoros Pangalos, alternate foreign minister in 
charge of European affairs, told the French paper QUEST-FRANCE 
that the settlement of the Bosnian crisis is a top priority for 
Greece in its capacity as president of the European Union [EU]. 
Mr. Pangalos said that we must resolve this problem before the 
spring or else the belligerent sides will embark on new war 
operations. He also noted: The military commanders are now 
prevented by the unfavorable weather conditions; we must exploit 
this fact and put an end to the war. 
  In his interview, the Greek minister points out that we are 
dedicated to the idea of inter-Balkan cooperation in the 
resolving of clashes. Mr. Pangalos added: However, the 
presidency would not do what Greece would like to do. He 
stressed: The presidency is not the departure point for Greek 
foreign policy, we will not make this mistake. 
  Mr. Pangalos also made it clear that the Greek Government 
will not use the presidency to upset the recognition of the 
republic of Skopje by most of the European countries. He said: 
This is not a EU problem. Mr. Pangalos pointed out that the 
hasty recognition of the former Yugoslav republics brought on 
the bloodshed in the Balkans. He stressed: If we had not 
recognized Bosnia, the massacre, or at least part of it, would 
have been avoided. 
  In conclusion, Theodhoros Pangalos stressed that we must 
avoid confrontations could develo into armed clashes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

