<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition Talks on Alternative Service Fail </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0501111294 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 5 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0501111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Talks on Alternative National </F>
Service Have Failed; Serious Conflict Burdens Coalition"] 
  [Text] Vienna -- No compromise is in sight in the ongoing 
quarrel among the coalition about the length of alternative 
national service. Quite the contrary, talks might have failed 
finally. 
  According to corresponding reports by both government 
parties, the negotiations on a new law on alternative national 
service, which lasted for months, have now failed. In fact, 
politicians declined to confirm this officially yesterday, but 
in hastily arranged news conferences and in numerous statements 
that were issued, both sides blamed each other for the failure. 
Thus, Defense Minister Werner Fasslabend (Austrian People's 
Party) announced that he has the impression that the Socialist 
Party of Austria [SPOe] was determined to prevent a successful 
conclusion. He no longer expects an agreement. 
  SPOe manager Cap stressed in an interview with DIE PRESSE 
yesterday: "The truth is that the Austrian People's Party 
[OeVP] has always wanted the commission [that decides whether 
the reasons cited by young men in favor of alternative national 
service are plausible]. For me Fasslabend signaled that there 
will be no more talks." 
  Shortly before the end of the year, agreement seemed within 
reach after renewed secret contacts between Chancellor Franz 
Vranitzky and Vice Chancellor Erhard Busek: They suggested 11 
months of alternative national service this year and delaying 
the decision as to whether and when it should be extended to 12 
months. 
  When difficulties occurred again in the negotiations between 
Fasslabend and Interior Minister Franz Loeschnak (SPOe), the 
OeVP finally lost its patience. 
  The result is that the old law went into effect at the 
beginning of the year. Alternative civilian service lasts eight 
months, but reasons must again be given before a commission. 
However, currently no personnel and no infrastructure are 
available for such a commission. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

