<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unemployment Expected To Reach 9 Percent in Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0501140594 Vienna DER STANDARD in German 5 Dec 93 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0501140594 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DER STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Unemployment Will Reach Its Highest </F>
Level in 30 Years in January"] 
  [Text] Vienna -- The Austrian unemployment rate rose from 
7.1 percent in November to 8.2 percent in December. It may even 
reach 9 percent in January. This is the highest unemployment 
rate since January 1959. The all-time low of 0.8 percent was 
registered in August 1974. 
  The decisive factor was the extraordinarily high seasonal 
unemployment in the construction industry. A similar 
development was also observed last year, but unemployment was .5 
percent lower at the time. Experts believe that the 
unemployment rate is currently higher than in January 1993, when 
8.4 percent was registered. 
  Erhard Fuerst, head of the Industrialists' Association 
Economic Department, dashed hopes that an upward economic trend 
might substantively improve the situation in the labor market. 
Austria needs an economic growth of at least 2.5 percent to 
prevent another rise in the unemployment rate. The forecasts, 
however, predict 1.5 percent for 1994. 
  According to a method of calculation applied in other 
industrialized countries, the unemployment rate in Austria 
stands at 4.3 percent. This method bases its calculations on 
the whole working population plus the unemployed, not just on 
employed persons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

