<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arms Exporters Encouraged by Rifkind's Gulf Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501183694 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1225 GMT 5 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0501183694 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Charles Miller, PRESS ASSOCIATION defence correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Arms exporters' hopes of huge orders from the Gulf 
receive a major boost this week with a five-day visit to the 
region by Defence Secretary Malcolm Rifkind. 
  His trip to Saudi Arabia, Oman, Bahrain and Kuwait comes 
just 
weeks after Defence Procurement Minister Jonathan Aitken visited 
the region to promote defence equipment. 
  Brian Newman, defence analyst at London stockbrokers 
Henderson Crossthwaite said: "The Middle East remains the 
market with the highest spend and best prospects for British 
industry. It is encouraging that the current government is 
giving exporters so much support." 
  Britain has already clinched massive contracts in the 
region, 
spearheaded by the 20 billion pounds sterlin Al Yamamah deal 
with Saudi Arabia. And industry is chasing numerous lucrative 
new contracts, including Hawk aircraft, Challenger tanks and 
minehunters for Saudi Arabia, Piranha armoured personnel 
carriers, AS90 howitzers and Super Lynx helicopters for Kuwait, 
and more Super Lynxes for Oman. Saudi Arabia is also 
considering leasing the Royal Navy's 1 billion pounds sterling 
fleet of four new Upholder submarines. 
  Mr. Rifkind, who left today, said: "This will be my first 
visit to the Middle East for more than a year, and my first ever 
visit to Oman. 
  "The UK is fully committed to supporting security and 
stability in the Gulf region and I hope my visit over the next 
few days will be seen as further evidence of that resolve." 

</TEXT>

