<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denktas Criticized Kliridhis on Defense Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0501150394 Nicosia Bayrak Radio in Turkish 1130 GMT 5 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0501150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Bayrak Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Rauf Denktas has concluded his contacts 
with representatives of the UN Security Council permanent member 
countries in Cyprus. 
  This morning, he separately received Chinese Ambassador Chen 
Zhenyou and French Ambassador Gerald Pavret de la Rochefordiere. 
He explained the Turkish position regarding the disarming of 
Cyprus. 
  In a statement after the meeting, Denktas said: The fact 
that Kliridhis announced that the agreement to sign a defense 
agreement with Greece was made in Greece, and the fact that he 
then offered the disarmament, tells the Turkish Cypriot side a 
lot of things; we must be very careful. 
  Denktas recalled that a former Greek Cypriot interior 
minister recently said there is a need to hoard some 20,000 to 
30,000 weapons. This means, Denktas said, that when the time 
comes, the EOKA [National Organization of Cypriot Fighters] 
movement will resume. Kliridhis' disarmament offer while this 
danger exists, reminds us of when Makarios returned the obsolete 
weapons to the British authorities in 1959, and then a year 
later, set up secret armies. People who went though those times 
must study the present proposals more carefully. The defense of 
the Turkish Cypriot side is bizonality, and its borders are 
being protected by Turkish troops today. 
  Denktas went on to say: We expect a change of mind and a 
change of heart from the the Greek Cypriot side. The Greek 
Cypriot government must stop the provocations of Greek Cypriot 
youths against Turkish Cypriots. If it cannot, then this must 
be done by the United Nations. 
  Denktas said he explained all these views to the Security 
Council officials who listened carefully and took notes. 
  Replying to a question, Denktas said that the Cyprus 
question 
is a national cause for Turkey and concerns the future of the 
Turkish Cypriots. Turkey has never used the Turkish Cypriots as 
a tool of compromise until now and will not do so in the future. 
Turkey is helping the Turkish Cypriots to ensure that a sound 
and equitable agreement is signed, in line with its own 
interests and those of the Turkish Cypriots. I am convinced 
that Turkey will continue to help us, Denktas said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

