<H3> <TI>   Former Official Questions Letter </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012180193 Hamburg DPA in German 1714 GMT 30 Dec 93--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD3012180193 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cologne [no date as received] (DPA) -- Heribert 
Hellenbroich, former president of the Office for the Protection 
of the Constitution [Bundesverfassungsschutz], views the letter 
claiming responsibility [for the death of Christian Democratic 
Union politician Bernhard Saelzer] as "a bad joke perpetrated by 
amateurs." He told the Friday [31 December] edition of the 
Cologne daily EXPRESS that the writers had made three decisive 
mistakes that had unmasked them: "First, the letter is very 
different from the confused linguistic style of the Red Army 
Faction [RAF]. Second, real terrorists would never claim to 
have tampered with the victim's car. They act professionally and 
do not talk about it. And third, they look for symbolic figures 
for their attacks. Mr. Saelzer was neither well known nor 
powerful enough to be a target for terrorists." 

</TEXT>

