<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe Says Bundeswehr Faces Year of Great Challenges </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012120293 Hamburg DPA in German 0951 GMT 30 Dec 93--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD3012120293 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- According to Defense Minister Volker 
Ruehe (Christian Democratic Union) the Bundeswehr faces a "great 
organizational and human challenge" in the coming year. In his 
Order of the Day at the end of the year, which was published 
today, Ruehe refers to the forthcoming internal restructuring, 
the closure of 66 command posts, and the transfer of numerous 
units to new locations. 
  In view of the difficult budgetary situation, it will also 
be 
necessary in 1994 to set clear priorities and to confine 
activities to the "core abilities" of the armed forces which 
derive from "security policy requirements," the minister said. 
At the same time, he appealed to those responsible to make 
particular efforts for conscripts, despite tight resources: 
"Even though the money is tight, the training of our young 
soldiers must take a prominent position in our common efforts 
for a healthy Bundeswehr." 
  In his Order of the Day, Ruehe referred in particular to the 
foreign missions of German servicemen. In the UN operations in 
Kampuchea, Somalia, Iraq, and the Adriatic as well as the aid 
flights to Bosnia, the Bundeswehr is fulfilling "daily the duty 
of Germany: People in need can count on our support." The armed 
forces are achieving "great things, at home and abroad" and they 
can be "justly proud" of this. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

