<H3> <TI>   Friuli's League-Led Regional Government Collapses </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR3012100393 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1758 GMT 29 
Dec 93--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3012100393 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "League-Led Regional Government Voted </F>
Down"] 
  [Text] Trieste, 29 Dec (ANSA) -- Friuli Giulia Venezia's 
regional government, Italy's first to be led by the Northern 
League, was voted out of power here today only six months after 
the elections that led to its formation in June. 
  The government's draft budget was rejected, then a 
no-confidence vote garnered 34 ayes and 25 noes, giving a 
fortnight for the formation of a new executive. The ouster was 
the first-ever by the regional assembly of the regional 
government. 
  The vote represents a new set-back for the previously 
all-conquering Northern League, which swept much of the board in 
Northern Italy in local elections held in June, but then failed 
to build on its breakthrough in voting in a group of major and 
less important cities early this month. 
  The majority that downed Friuli Venezia Giulia's government 
consisted of Left and Christian Democrats, Socialists, the 
Communists, the Friuli Autonomy League, the Greens, and a couple 
of independents. Opposition to the no-confidence motion came 
from the League, the Republicans and the Liberals, who formed 
the governing alliance, plus the neo-Fascist Italian Social 
Movement and the Slate for Trieste. 
  The political parties have been negotiating for the 
formation 
of a new majority for several days. One idea is a Christian 
Democrat-League alliance, which is being urged by the 
neo-Fascists and the Slate for Trieste, and another a Left 
Democrat-led coalition including the Communists, the Greens and 
the Friuli Autonomy League with support from Christian Democrats 
and Socialists. 

</TEXT>

