<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Says NATO Needs `New Initiative' on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0401124394 Paris AFP in English 1226 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0401124394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 4 (AFP) -- The NATO summit in Brussels 
next week should consider a "new initiative" to revive the peace 
process in the former Yugoslavia, French Foreign Minister Alain 
Juppe said here Tuesday [4 January]. 
  Juppe, presenting his New Year wishes to the press, said 
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) leaders at their 
summit meeting next Monday and Tuesday should "reflect on a new 
initiative, either to guarantee implementation of the peace 
plan, or force the parties to give up their warlike plans and 
find an accord." 
  Bosnia's warring Moslems, Serbs and Croats are to meet in 
two 
weeks in Geneva to resume peace talks. 
  Juppe also stressed the need to maintain pressure on the 
Bosnian parties and for the United Nations to find an "urgent 
response" on the role and means of the UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) in Bosnia. 
  On Monday, French General Jean Cot, commander in chief of 
the 
30,000-strong UNPROFOR in ex-Yugoslavia, complained of the 
"humiliations" suffered by the UN troops and said the force was 
ready for an "offensive intervention" in Bosnia. 
  "I understand the feeling of revolt and anger" of UNPROFOR 
officials, Juppe said. "We cannot allow ourselves to be 
discouraged." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57979 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu002_i_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-002 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Criticizes Zhirinovskiy, Rules Out Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0301113294 Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS in French 3 Jan 93 
p 14 </F>

<F P=103> BR0301113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Russia: Zhirinovskiy Persona Non </F>
Grata in France"] 
  [Text] European Minister Alain Lamassoure said yesterday 
that France "cannot tolerate" the statements made by Russian 
ultranationalist leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, indicating that 
he could not, in this context, enter French territory, contrary 
to his expectations. According to the minister, "the statements 
made on Bulgaria, the Romanian people, the Baltic states, 
Finland, Turkey, and other countries are unaccceptable." 
Zhirinovskiy warned Germany -- which denied him an entry visa 
-- that he would launch a "Third World War" if he ever came to 
power in Moscow, according to the weekly WELT AM SONNTAG. 
Zhirinovskiy announced that he would send "300,000 Russian 
troops" to Germany if he became head of government. 

</TEXT>

