<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Talks in Vienna End Without Results </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0501175494 Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network in German 
1700 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0501175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Elisa Wasch] </F>
  [Text] The result of the negotiations in Vienna is 
practically zero. Muslims and Croats definitively agreed only 
on another meeting. The presidents of Croatia and Bosnia, 
Tudjman and Izetbegovic, will meet in Bonn on Saturday [8 
January] to agree on further details for a cease-fire in central 
Bosnia. Currently, the Muslims are engaged in a successful 
offensive against the Croats there. 
  However, cease-fires are not a way out of the crisis, 
European Union negotiator Lord Owen says: 
  [Begin Owen recording, in English with superimposed German 
translation] We have never argued for cease-fires. We have 
always said that there must be a political solution, and I have 
not changed my opinion about that. Only after a political 
agreement has been achieved can there be a ceasefire. [end 
recording] 
  However, the political agreement is not yet there. The 
Croats still do not want to discuss access to the Adriatic Sea 
for the Muslims in the Croatian town of Neum. Only the Croatian 
town of Ploce is being discussed as the location of a Muslim 
free port. 
  There is no agreement on future borders, either. Only 
meetings between various Muslim and Croatian committees have 
been agreed, which are supposed to discuss details of an 
exchange of prisoners and of humanitarian aid. 

</TEXT>

