<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Owen Blames All Yugoslav Leaders for War in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601200594 Hamburg DPA in German 1844 GMT 6 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0601200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- In a sweeping criticism of all parties 
involved in the Yugoslavia conflict, today in Bonn European 
Union mediator Lord Owen apportioned equal blame for the 
continuation of the war to all the leaders. Together with the 
other co-chairman of the Geneva Yugoslavia conference, Thorvald 
Stoltenberg, Lord Owen spoke with [German] Foreign Minister 
Klaus Kinkel about the civil war situation. While Kinkel 
expressly warned against optimism, Lord Owen went a step further 
and said that the leaders of all the warring parties were 
indifferent to the fates of the people "because they have lost 
touch with reality." They still thought that advantages were to 
be derived from continuing the fighting. 
  The discussion with the two Yugoslavia mediators followed a 
meeting between Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic, in the 
run-up to a two-way conference between Presidents Franjo Tudjman 
(Croatia) and Alija Izetbegovic (Bosnia-Herzegovina), who 
planned to meet at their own request in Bonn on Saturday [8 
January]. 
  Stoltenberg, too, spoke of a "deterioration in the 
situation." He regretted the lack of UN forces to enforce the UN 
Security Council resolutions, and warned against further force 
withdrawals. 

</TEXT>

