<H3> <TI>   Kinkel: NATO To Offer East `Closer Cooperation' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701141894 Hamburg DPA in German 1331 GMT 7 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0701141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- According to German Foreign Minister 
Klaus Kinkel, NATO will offer the East closer cooperation, but 
not full membership, at its summit in Brussels on Monday [10 
January] and Tuesday. Full membership, which would create new 
rifts between the Central and East European states and the CIS 
republics, could not be in the interests of all involved, the 
foreign minister said in his annual survey of foreign policy on 
Friday. 
  A fundamental decision is to be announced in Brussels, 
Kinkel 
announced. Bringing the states of Central and East Europe 
closer to Western institutions is a top priority of German 
foreign policy. After taking over the presidency of the European 
Union on 1 July 1994, Bonn will work hard on the early 
conclusion of a cooperation agreement with Russia. This would 
bring Moscow into increasingly close partnership. 

</TEXT>

