<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   `No Differences' Between Kohl, Ruehe on NATO Expansion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701125894 Hamburg DPA in German 1115 GMT 7 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0701125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn (DPA) -- According to government spokesman 
Dieter Vogel, there are no differences of opinion between 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Defense Minister Volker Ruehe on the 
issue of expanding NATO to include East Europe. Speaking to the 
press in Bonn on Friday [7 January], Vogel rejected a report in 
the HANNOVERSCHE ALLGEMEINE ZEITUNG that Ruehe is opposed to 
Kohl in this matter. 
  According to Vogel, the minister telephoned the chancellor 
on 
Friday to assure him that he agreed with him and Foreign 
Minister Klaus Kinkel that Hungary, Poland, and the Czech and 
Slovak Republics should be the first to be offered the U.S. 
Partnership for Peace proposal at the NATO summit in Brussels 
next Monday. The Defense Ministry said that Ruehe takes the view 
that the NATO expansion should be shaped "as a process which 
should be initiated at the NATO summit." The minister sees the 
Partnership for Peace initiative as an important stage in this 
process, but not as a substitute for the expansion of NATO. 
[Passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

