<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Reschedules Peruvian Debt Repayment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501140194 Hamburg DPA in German 0946 GMT 5 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0501140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA)--The Federal Government is to allow Peru 
to defer the repayment of around 150 million German marks [DM] 
in public debts. A corresponding rescheduling agreement has now 
been signed, the Federal Finance Ministry said today. The 
agreement gives Peru breathing space for repaying to Germany the 
majority of the debts, which would otherwise have been due by 31 
March 1996. The repayment has now been extended over 15 to 20 
years. The debts are based on credits as part of German 
development aid, Hermes-guaranteed export credits, as well as 
trade deals with the former GDR. Peru is to be excused 
repayment of DM30 million of the development aid credit if it 
uses one-third of that sum to protect and maintain the 
environment. 
  The new debt regulation serves as further support for the 
reform process in Peru, the Finance Ministry said. Peru has 
already brought inflation under control, through its efforts 
since 1990 to stabilize the economy: Inflation dropped from 
7,600 percent in 1990 to 57 percent in 1992, and it is to be 
reduced further to 27 percent. In 1991, real economic growth, 
of 2.5 percent, was achieved again. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

