<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continues Consultations With Parties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0601103594 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1321 GMT 5 
Jan 93--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0601103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ciampi Concludes Consultations"] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 5 Jan (ANSA) -- Prime Minister Carlo Azeglio 
Ciampi on Wednesday [5 January] plans to conclude consultations 
with minor parties in view of the January 12 parliamentary 
debate on no-confidence motions submitted to the Senate and 
Lower House. 
  After his meetings yesterday with the major parties, Ciampi 
this morning met with delegations from the Network, Green and 
Communist Refoundation parties. In the afternoon, after a 
working lunch with the director of the International Monetary 
Fund, Ciampi will receive representatives from the Italian 
Social Movement, Sudtyroler Volkspartei [South Tirol People's 
Party] and Union Valdotaine [Valdostan Union]. 
  The traditional government parties yesterday urged Ciampi to 
stay at his post and delay a vote until combined European 
Parliament and early elections can be held in June, while most 
of the smaller opposition parties, as well as the Left 
Democrats, the Northern League and the Italian Social Movement 
want elections as soon as possible. 
  The no-confidence motions were submitted by Federalist Party 
leader Marco Pannella and were signed mostly by members of the 
four governing parties -- Christian Democrats, Socialists, 
Social Democrats and Liberals. The premier's resignation in fact 
would prevent the president from dissolving parliament until a 
new coalition cabinet is formed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
